*DESCRIPTION_START
The black rod iron gate in the low metal fence surrounding this small cemetary,
creaks mysteriously as it swings back and forth of its own volition. Several
chunks of headstones coated with grime lay toppled atop the now unmarked graves.
The eyes of several stone statues which depict gargoyles and sinister looking
angels seem to follow your every move. An old rotten barrel leans against the
one headstone that has not yet succumbed to time and fallen over.
*DESCRIPTION_END
EXIT NE 1060
EXIT S 1062
ITEM 0 1907
ITEM 1 1032 ADJ1=222 ADJ2=586
*DESCRIPTION_START ITEM EXAMINE 1
Probably once used to hold the trash cleaned from around the gravesites the
barrel now only seems to keep the headstone it leans upon from falling into
the dirt.
*DESCRIPTION_END
MONSTER_GROUP 114
VARIABLE spotta
IFPREVERB LOOK 0
  CLEARVERB
 IFVAR spotta < 3
  ECHO PLAYER You wonder who would have the sick sense of humor to write, "Failed Experiments", on the headstone. Those are the only words the can be made out though, as the years have covered the rest of the headstone with dirt.
 ENDIF
  IFVAR spotta => 3
    ECHO PLAYER With most of the dirt removed you can now make out the phrase, "Orinasum Jalea Durinium!"
  ENDIF
ENDIF
IFPREVERB SPIT 0
  CLEARVERB
  ADD spotta 1
   IFVAR spotta < 3
     ECHO PLAYER Some of the dirt falls off with the force of your spit!
     ECHO OTHERS %N spits on the headstone and then carefully rubs away some of the dirt.
   ENDIF
     IFVAR spotta = 3
       ECHO PLAYER Most of the dirt has fallen away, and you can now see another phrase below the other one...
       ECHO OTHERS %N spits on the headstone and then carefully rubs away most of the dirt, exposing another phrase below the other one..
     ENDIF
       IFVAR spotta > 3
         ECHO PLAYER You shine up the headstone some more with your spit.
         ECHO OTHERS %N shines up the headstone some more with %h spit.
       ENDIF
ENDIF
IFSAY Orinasum_jalea_durinium!
  ECHO PLAYER You feel your eyes glow, almost painfully, for a moment causing you to shut them. When you again open them you can see your surroundings much more clearly..
  ECHO OTHERS %N's eyes glow a painful red for a moment, causing %i to shut them. When %N once again opens %h eyes, you can still see a faint reddish hue around their pupils...
  EQUAL FLAG1 1
  EQUAL ROUNDTIME 5
ENDIF
IFVERB SEARCH -1
  IFVAR FLAG1 = 1
    ECHO PLAYER You enhanced perception leads you to finding a skull buried in the dirt of the grave. You carefully pick it up and place it within the barrel.
    ECHO OTHERS %N carefully sifts through the dirt of the grave and then picks up a dirty skull, which %s carefully places within the barrel.
    NEWPUT 1 288 ADJ1=95
    EQUAL FLAG1 0
    EQUAL ROUNDTIME 10
  ENDIF
   IFVAR FLAG1 ! 1
     ECHO PLAYER You don't find anything of note.
     ECHO OTHERS %N desultorily searches the area for a while.
   ENDIF
ENDIF
;
NUMBER 1062
NAME Flower Garden
FIXED_LIGHT
OUTDOOR_FLOOR
REGION 11
*DESCRIPTION_START
Now barren of their once gorgeous blooms are several rows of lifeless rose
bushes, their withered blackened trunks covered with mold. Dried bulbs,
their tubular shapes now exposed to the elements, still are arranged in a
circle around a raised mound of barren ground. A huge pile of rubble stacked
between the sides of the mansion and a tall retaining wall prevents you from
going any direction except back the way you just came.
*DESCRIPTION_END
EXIT N 1061
MONSTER_GROUP 114
;
NUMBER 1064
NAME Pattern Chamber
FIXED_LIGHT
ASTRAL
REGION 11
CHANNEL 133
*DESCRIPTION_START
A subdued light flows from the mysterious floor of this chamber and covers
the whole area with a hazy glow. The bare stone walls offer no clue as to
the meaning of the strange tiles imbedded into the floor. Nine tiles in all
make up the whole of the chamber, each tile holding a different pattern.
A closer observation of the patterns reveals that some have begun to show
the signs of age, as if they have been neglected for some time...
*DESCRIPTION_END
EXIT O 1063
ITEM 0 434
ITEM 1 434
ITEM 2 434
ITEM 3 434
ITEM 4 434
ITEM 5 434
ITEM 6 434
ITEM 7 434
ITEM 8 434
*DESCRIPTION_START ITEM EXAMINE 0
This pattern is drawn to resemble three wavy lines, one atop the other.
*DESCRIPTION_END
*DESCRIPTION_START ITEM EXAMINE 1
This pattern is drawn to resemble a simple stick figure of a humanoid.
*DESCRIPTION_END
*DESCRIPTION_START ITEM EXAMINE 2
This pattern is drawn to resemble a simple stick figure of an animal.
*DESCRIPTION_END
*DESCRIPTION_START ITEM EXAMINE 3
This pattern is drawn to resemble a sword crossed over what appear to be
a chest.
*DESCRIPTION_END
*DESCRIPTION_START ITEM EXAMINE 4
An eight pointed star is inscribed upon this pattern.
*DESCRIPTION_END
*DESCRIPTION_START ITEM EXAMINE 5
This pattern is drawn to resemble a mountain range.
*DESCRIPTION_END
*DESCRIPTION_START ITEM EXAMINE 6
This pattern is drawn to resemble a forest.
*DESCRIPTION_END
*DESCRIPTION_START ITEM EXAMINE 7
This pattern is drawn to resemble an ocean wave.
*DESCRIPTION_END
*DESCRIPTION_START ITEM EXAMINE 8
This pattern is drawn to resemble a city.
*DESCRIPTION_END
IFENTRY
  IFVAR SKILL23 => 1
    ECHO PLAYER Faint emanations of magical power flow from the patterns into your senses.
    ECHO OTHERS %N gazes at the patterns with curiousity.
  ENDIF
ENDIF
IFVERB RECALL -1
   IFVAR SKILL32 => 3
     ECHO PLAYER The use of Patterns in magic, you know, has not been studied, or applied, in many years. Most call it a lost art, since practitioners of it closely guarded its secrets. The last mage known to practice the use of Patterns was a man
     echo all named Cristalos, and the art of Pattern Magic died along with him.
   ENDIF
ENDIF
IFPREVERB GO 0
  CLEARVERB
  DISBAND
    IFVAR FLAG2 = 0
      IFVAR INTNUM45 = 2
        ECHO PLAYER You step onto the pattern and it begins to glow with a golden hue.
        ECHO OTHERS %N steps onto the pattern, which begins to glow with a golden hue.
        EQUAL FLAG2 1
      ENDIF
      IFVAR INTNUM45 ! 2
        ECHO PLAYER A chiding voice speaks in your mind, "You are not prepared to attempt this yet, find the other hidden secrets first.
        ECHO OTHERS %N steps onto the square and then shakes %h head as if trying to clear it.
      ENDIF
    ENDIF
      IFVAR FLAG2 > 1
        ECHO PLAYER  You sense that you have broken the chain of the pattern.
        ECHO OTHERS %N sighs as %s steps onto the square.
        EQUAL FLAG2 0
      ENDIF
ENDIF
